20adversaries%20at%20a%20time%20of%20high%20geopolitical%20tensions%20by%20marrying%20the%20two%20reconnaissance%20methods%3A%20operating%20a%20crewed%20spy%20satellite%20in%20space.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EManned%20space%20operations%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22An%20illustration%20of%20the%20Manned%20Orbiting%20Laboratory.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e445eec62ab5daf822598%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22905%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EAn%20illustration%20of%20the%20Manned%20Orbiting%20Laboratory.%3Cp%3EUS%20Air%20Force%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Manned%20Orbiting%20Laboratory%20(MOL)%20was%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nasa.gov%2Fhistory%2F50-years-ago-nasa-benefits-from-manned-orbiting-laboratory-cancellation%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ejoint%20project%20between%20the%20US%20Air%20Force%20and%20the%20National%20Reconnaissance%20Office%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20prompted%20by%20the%20need%20for%20rapid%20and%20reliable%20intelligence%20following%20the%20Cuban%20Missile%20Crisis%20in%201962%20and%20during%20the%20Cold%20War%20and%20the%20Vietnam%20War.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThen-US%20Secretary%20of%20Defense%20Robert%20McNamara%20publicly%20unveiled%20the%20program%20in%20December%201963%2C%20and%20President%20Lyndon%20B.%20Johnson%20formally%20approved%20the%20project%20in%20August%201965.%20Though%20the%20program%20was%20intended%20to%20give%20the%20US%20military%20a%20reconnaissance%20vantage%20point%20in%20space%2C%20it%20was%20portrayed%20as%20an%20operation%20to%20find%20what%20humans%20are%20capable%20of%20in%20space.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThis%20program%20will%20bring%20us%20new%20knowledge%20about%20what%20man%20is%20able%20to%20do%20in%20space%2C%26quot%3B%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nro.gov%2FPortals%2F135%2Fdocuments%2Fhistory%2Fcsnr%2Fprograms%2Fdocs%2FMOL_Compendium_August_2015.pdf%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EJohnson%20said%20at%20the%20time%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%26quot%3BIt%20will%20enable%20us%20to%20relate%20that%20ability%20to%20the%20defense%20of%20America.%20It%20will%20develop%20technology%20and%20equipment%20which%20will%20help%20advance%20manned%20and%20unmanned%20space%20flights.%20And%20it%20will%20make%20it%20possible%20to%20perform%20their%20new%20and%20rewarding%20experiments.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOperations%20on%20the%20MOL%20began%20in%20the%20spring%20of%201964.%20The%20MOL%20sought%20to%20obtain%20high-resolution%20photographic%20imagery%20of%20foreign%20adversaries%20like%20the%20Soviet%20Union.%20While%20satellites%20effectively%20gathered%20intelligence%2C%20they%20faced%20limitations%20like%20cloud%20cover%20and%20time%20delays%20in%20retrieval%20that%20prevented%20them%20from%20consistently%20taking%20useful%20photographic%20imagery.%20An%20operator%20onboard%20the%20satellite%20would%20allow%20them%20to%20circumvent%20those%20issues%20and%20identify%20where%20and%20when%20to%20capture%20an%20image%20in%20real-time.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20idea%20was%20humans%20could%20help%20pick%20targets%20in%20real%20time%2C%20they%20could%20identify%20cloud%20cover%20and%20save%20film%2C%26quot%3B%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nro.gov%2Fnews-media-featured-stories%2Fnews-media-archive%2FNews-Article%2FArticle%2F3208288%2Fthe-story-of-the-manned-orbiting-laboratory-part-one%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ERichard%20Truly%2C%20a%20former%20MOL%20crewmember%2C%20said%20in%202022%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%26quot%3BThe%20system%20was%20resource-limited%20because%20it%20was%20a%20film%20system%2C%20not%20electronic%20like%20we%20have%20now.%20But%20the%20whole%20idea%20was%20to%20have%20a%20far%20more%20capable%20intelligence%20capability%20because%20you%20had%20people%20there%20that%20could%20think%20and%20act%20and%20take%20action%20in%20real%20time%20during%20the%20flight.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EA%2060-foot-long%20space%20station%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221270%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22a%20man%20points%20to%20a%20model%20of%20the%20Manned%20Orbiting%20Laboratory.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e5255ec62ab5daf82262b%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22735%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EAn%20early%20version%20of%20the%20MOL.%3Cp%3ENational%20Reconnaissance%20Office%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20MOL%20program%20originally%20planned%20to%20have%20six%20launches%20with%20a%20flight%20duration%20of%20two%20to%20four%20weeks%20%E2%80%94%20an%20ambitious%20feat%20given%20that%20the%20longest%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fnasas-moonwalking-men-2012-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ea%20human%20had%20been%20in%20space%3C%2Fa%3E%20previously%20was%20eight%20days%20during%20NASA's%20Gemini%20V%20mission%20in%201965.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20two-man%20crew%20would%20lift%20off%20in%20a%20modified%20Gemini%20capsule%20atop%20a%20spacecraft%20that%20would%20house%20the%20MOL.%20After%20the%20flight%20duration%2C%20the%20capsule%20would%20detach%20and%20return%20to%20Earth%20while%20the%20MOL%20would%20remain%20in%20orbit.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EProposed%20configuration%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221003%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20crew%20assembles%20the%20MOL%20vehicle.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e52bcdcdb354a98562362%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22742%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EA%20crew%20assembles%20the%20MOL%20vehicle.%3Cp%3ENational%20Reconnaissance%20Office%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20proposed%20configuration%20of%20the%20MOL%20was%20that%20the%20front%20of%20the%20spacecraft%20would%20house%20the%20transfer%20tunnel%20and%20fuel%20cells%2C%20behind%20that%20would%20be%20the%20laboratory%20divided%20into%20work%20and%20living%20compartments%2C%20and%20the%20rear%20of%20the%20spacecraft%20would%20be%20the%20equipment%20module%20and%20breathing%20tanks.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAside%20from%20the%20laboratory%20where%20astronauts%20would%20conduct%20experiments%2C%20the%20primary%20payload%20of%20the%20MOL%20would%20be%20a%20telescope%20used%20for%20military%20reconnaissance.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20telescope%20was%20designed%20to%20have%20a%20primary%20mirror%20that%20was%2072%20inches%20in%20diameter%2C%20and%20its%20imaging%20system%20was%20codenamed%20Dorian.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EAstronaut%20selection%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22670%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22MOL%20astronauts%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659f92716979d73718225278%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22503%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EMOL%20astronauts%20Robert%20T.%20Herres%2C%20Robert%20H.%20Lawrence%2C%20Donald%20H.%20Peterson%2C%20and%20James%20A.%20Abrahamson.%3Cp%3EUS%20Air%20Force%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20three%20rounds%2C%20the%20US%20Air%20Force%20selected%2017%20pilots%20to%20participate%20in%20the%20MOL%20program.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20of%20the%20pilots%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Farnaldo-tamayo-mendez-first-black-person-astronaut-cosmonaut-reach-orbit-2020-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ERobert%20H.%20Lawrence%2C%20was%20the%20first%20African%20American%20selected%20to%20be%20an%20astronaut%20by%20any%20national%20space%20program%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Lawrence%20was%20among%20the%20final%20selection%20group%20completed%20in%20June%201967%2C%20but%20he%20died%20in%20an%20F-104%20Starfighter%20crash%20in%20late%201967.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EAstronaut%20training%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221626%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22MOL%20astronaut%20training.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e598c6979d7371821e431%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221267%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EMOL%20astronaut%20training.%3Cp%3ECSNR%20Reference%20Collection%2FNRO%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EMOL%20crewmembers%20had%20a%20busy%20training%20regiment%20to%20prepare%20for%20various%20unexpected%20events%20while%20in%20space.%20They%20were%20given%20survival%20training%20to%20prepare%20for%20unexpected%20deorbiting%20in%20the%20case%20of%20spacecraft%20leaks.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECrewmembers%20also%20trained%20in%20spacecraft%20simulators%20and%20went%20through%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fus-special-operators-show-off-skills-in-combat-diver-competition-2023-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eunderwater%20training%3C%2Fa%3E%20at%20the%20Navy%20dive%20school%20in%20Key%20West%2C%20Florida.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMost%20importantly%2C%20they%20received%20training%20with%20the%20National%20Photographic%20Interpretation%20Center%20to%20learn%20more%20about%20photographic%20intelligence%20and%20subject%20recognition%20%E2%80%94%20a%20central%20part%20of%20the%20MOL's%20program%20objective.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3ENo%20spacewalk%20needed%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22985%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20suited%20crewmember%20in%20a%20mockup%20of%20the%20MOL%20crew%20cabin%20showing%20the%20narrow%20tunnel%20leading%20to%20the%20Gemini-B%20capsule.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659f9e326979d73718225294%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22781%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EA%20suited%20crewmember%20in%20a%20mockup%20of%20the%20MOL%20crew%20cabin%20showing%20the%20narrow%20tunnel%20leading%20to%20the%20Gemini-B%20capsule.%3Cp%3ENRO%2FNASA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20external%20design%20for%20the%20MOL's%20spacecraft%20was%20similar%20to%20that%20of%20NASA's%20Gemini.%20But%20the%20major%20difference%20was%20that%20a%20hatch%20cut%20into%20the%20heat%20shield%20allowed%20astronauts%20to%20pass%20between%20the%20capsule%20at%20the%20front%20of%20the%20spacecraft%20to%20the%20laboratory%20and%20living%20quarters%20in%20the%20back%20without%20a%20spacewalk.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3ENarrow%20passageways%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221752%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Astronaut%20crawling%20in%20space%20suit%20in%20MOL.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e59c76979d7371821e435%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221221%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EAstronaut%20crawling%20in%20space%20suit%20in%20MOL.%3Cp%3ECSNR%20Reference%20Collection%2FNRO%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EAstronauts%20required%20a%20special%20spacesuit%20that%20was%20flexible%20enough%20to%20allow%20them%20to%20crawl%20through%20the%20narrow%20passageway%20between%20the%20Gemini%20capsule%20and%20the%20laboratory%20on%20the%20MOL.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3ESpecial%20spacesuits%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221628%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22MOL%20astronaut%20flight%20suit.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e59176979d7371821e42c%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221276%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EMOL%20astronaut%20flight%20suit.%3Cp%3ECSNR%20Reference%20Collection%2FNRO%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThough%20the%20spacesuit%20never%20actually%20made%20it%20into%20space%2C%20NASA%20used%20the%20technology%20behind%20it%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fspacesuit-design-history-timeline-changes-nasa-2018-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efuture%20spacesuit%20development%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EExperiments%20and%20reconnaissance%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221724%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22MOL%20controls%20model.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e5ac8dcdb354a98562388%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221348%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EMOL%20controls%20model.%3Cp%3ECSNR%20Reference%20Collection%2FNRO%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20the%20existence%20of%20the%20MOL%20was%20publicly%20known%2C%20its%20mission%20to%20gather%20photographic%20intelligence%20on%20foreign%20adversaries%20was%20highly%20classified.%20However%2C%20press%20coverage%20at%20the%20time%20conveyed%20the%20MOL%20as%20a%20reconnaissance%20mission%2C%20and%20the%20top%20secret%20classification%20of%20the%20program%20prevented%20officials%20from%20denying%20the%20claims.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAmid%20concerns%20about%20how%20other%20countries%20would%20react%20to%20the%20US%20military%20operating%20in%20space%2C%20Louis%20Mazza%2C%20Chief%20Program%20Security%20officer%20of%20the%20NRO%2C%20proposed%20to%20%26quot%3Badmit%20we%20have%20a%20DOD%20manned%20orbital%20laboratory%2C%20and%20its%20mission%20is%20to%20determine%20man's%20potential%20usefulness%20in%20space.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThus%2C%20MOL%20operations%20expanded%20to%20include%2010%20experiments%20called%20Project%20Manifold%2C%20which%20studied%20cell%20growth%20and%20new%20technologies%20aboard%20the%20spacecraft.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3ETest%20launch%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221280%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20only%20operational%20launch%20of%20the%20MOL%20program%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e51d86979d7371821e401%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22720%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20only%20operational%20launch%20of%20the%20MOL%20program%2C%20a%20Gemini-B%20capsule%20and%20a%20MOL%20mockup%20atop%20a%20Titan-IIIC%20rocket.%3Cp%3ENASA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20first%20and%20only%20launch%20of%20the%20MOL%20program%20took%20place%20at%20Cape%20Canaveral%20Air%20Force%20Station%20on%20November%203%2C%201966%2C%20two%20years%20after%20work%20on%20the%20project%20began.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20launch%20was%20only%20a%20test%2C%20consisting%20of%20a%20Gemini%20capsule%20and%20a%20mockup%20of%20the%20MOL%20without%20the%20imaging%20payload%20atop%20a%20Titan-IIIC%20rocket.%20The%20mockup%20entered%20Earth's%20orbit%20and%20released%20three%20satellites.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Project%20Manifold%20experiments%20were%20also%20aboard%20the%20MOL%20mockup%20and%20were%20intended%20to%20operate%20for%2075%20days%2C%20but%20the%20MOL%20stopped%20transmitting%20data%20after%20just%2030%20days%20before%20decaying%20from%20orbit%20on%20January%209%2C%201967.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EConcerns%20and%20criticisms%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22822%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22MOL%20vehicle.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659e5a056979d7371821e43b%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221296%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EMOL%20vehicle.%3Cp%3ECSNR%20Reference%20Collection%2FNRO%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ESince%20the%20program's%20inception%2C%20it%20was%20met%20with%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nro.gov%2Fnews-media-featured-stories%2Fnews-media-archive%2FNews-Article%2FArticle%2F3249852%2Fthe-story-of-the-manned-orbiting-laboratory-part-three%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecriticism%20and%20skepticism%3C%2Fa%3E%20surrounding%20the%20MOL's%20value.%20By%201969%2C%20the%20program%20was%20years%20behind%20schedule%20and%20over%20budget.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESince%20the%20MOL%20was%20operating%20under%20the%20guise%20of%20testing%20man's%20%26quot%3Bpotential%20usefulness%20in%20space%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20program%20publicly%20seemed%20all%20too%20similar%20to%20NASA's%20Apollo%20program%2C%20so%20much%20so%20that%20Congress%20saw%20it%20as%20a%20duplicate%20and%20cut%20its%20funding%20by%2060%25%20in%201967.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMOL%20advocates%20pushed%20to%20combine%20the%20USAF%20efforts%20with%20NASA%2C%20which%20was%20met%20with%20pushback%20as%20it%20would%20damage%20NASA's%20image%20as%20a%20peaceful%20agency.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAs%20budget%20cuts%20and%20delays%20plagued%20the%20MOL%2C%20its%20technology%20for%20military%20reconnaissance%20was%20becoming%20obsolete%2C%20rendering%20the%20program's%20original%20intent%20virtually%20useless.%3C%2Fp%3